oc:kn_17854cf2 a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:WorkflowStrategy ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When writing skills that enforce rules or requirements" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Bulletproof discipline-enforcing skills by: (1) closing every loophole explicitly with specific negations, (2) adding 'Violating the letter IS violating the spirit' principle, (3) building rationalization tables from test data, (4) creating red flags lists for self-checking." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Agents are smart and will find loopholes under pressure. Explicit anti-rationalization counters prevent predictable compliance failures." ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

oc:kn_2f712f35 a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:PerformanceProfile ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When writing SKILL.md content" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Target word counts: getting-started workflows <150 words, frequently-loaded skills <200 words, other skills <500 words. Move details to --help, use cross-references, compress examples." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Skills share context window with system prompt, conversation history, and other skills. Every token competes for attention." ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

oc:kn_3530bdb3 a oc:Heuristic,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When deciding whether to use a flowchart in skill documentation" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Use flowcharts ONLY for non-obvious decision points, process loops where you might stop too early, and 'when to use A vs B' decisions. Never for reference material, code examples, or linear instructions." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Flowcharts consume tokens and add complexity. They only add value when the decision logic is genuinely ambiguous." ;
    oc:severityLevel "MEDIUM" .

oc:kn_364e2a68 a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:Procedure ;
    oc:appliesToContext "Creating or editing any skill" ;
    oc:directiveContent "1. RED: Run pressure scenarios WITHOUT skill → document agent failures verbatim. 2. GREEN: Write minimal skill addressing those specific failures → verify compliance. 3. REFACTOR: Find new rationalizations → add explicit counters → re-test until bulletproof." ;
    oc:stepOrder 1 .

oc:kn_63840949 a oc:DesignPrinciple,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When adding code examples to skills" ;
    oc:directiveContent "One excellent code example beats many mediocre ones. Choose the most relevant language, make it complete and runnable, comment explaining WHY, from a real scenario." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Agents are good at porting — one great example in one language is sufficient and avoids maintenance burden." ;
    oc:severityLevel "MEDIUM" .

oc:kn_b9ca5552 a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:RecoveryTactic ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When skill testing shows non-compliance" ;
    oc:directiveContent "When agent fails GREEN phase despite having the skill, meta-test by asking: 'You read the skill and chose wrong anyway. How could the skill have been written differently?' Three diagnoses: (1) skill was clear but agent ignored → add stronger foundational principle, (2) skill should have said X → add their suggestion, (3) agent didn't see section Y → reorganize for prominence." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Distinguishes documentation problems from organizational problems from agent willfulness, enabling targeted fixes." ;
    oc:severityLevel "MEDIUM" .

oc:kn_c0678b48 a oc:Constraint,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "Always, for both new skills and edits to existing skills" ;
    oc:directiveContent "NO SKILL WITHOUT A FAILING TEST FIRST. Write skill before testing? Delete it. Start over. Edit skill without testing? Same violation. No exceptions for 'simple additions', 'just adding a section', or 'documentation updates'." ;
    oc:hasRationale "If you didn't watch an agent fail without the skill, you don't know if the skill teaches the right thing." ;
    oc:severityLevel "CRITICAL" .

oc:kn_f15729a5 a oc:Constraint,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When deciding whether to create a skill" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Skills are NOT narratives about how you solved a problem once. Skills ARE reusable techniques, patterns, tools, and reference guides." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Narratives are too specific and not reusable. Skills must generalize across projects and instances." ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

oc:kn_f7d33dd4 a oc:AntiPattern,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When writing YAML frontmatter for any skill" ;
    oc:directiveContent "NEVER summarize the skill's process or workflow in the description field. Description = triggering conditions only, starting with 'Use when...'." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Testing revealed that descriptions summarizing workflow cause Claude to follow the description instead of reading the full skill body, creating a shortcut that skips the actual skill content." ;
    oc:severityLevel "CRITICAL" .

